Penney Co.'s JCP board Friday, becoming the second big investor to leave the struggling department-store operator's board in recent weeks. Vornado said it has a 6.1% stake in Penney.

Headlines.Author: Melodie Warner
Headlines.Headline: Vornado to Book Narrower Loss on Toys 'R' Us in 3rd Quarter

PARAGRAPH.#text: Vornado Realty Trust VNO said its third quarter will reflect a narrower loss from its share of Toys "R" Us Inc.'s fiscal second-quarter results. The real estate investment trust bought a stake in Toys 'R' Us in 2005, along with private-equity firms Bain Capital LLC and Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., for $6.6 billion. PARAGRAPH.#text: Toys "R" Us Inc. reported Friday a fiscal third-quarter loss that was flat with a year earlier as margins improved but videogame sales fell sharply. Toys "R" Us has made a number of investments to position itself for future growth--including the expansion of its e-commerce business and store conversions to integrate toy and juvenile products. Last month, the retailer bought a 70% interest in its existing licensed operations throughout Asia, and it has the option to buy the remaining stake in the future.

PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Vornado Realty LP plans to sell $400 million of 10-year notes in the U.S. credit market Wednesday. The New York-based company is an affiliate of Vornado Realty Trust VNO, a real-estate investment trust that owns and manages commercial properties, primarily in markets in New York and the District of Columbia.

Headlines.Author: Karen Talley
Headlines.Headline: JC Penney Agrees To Let Vornado Realty Increase Stake In Retailer

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Karen Talley Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--J.C. Penney Co. JCP has agreed to allow Vornado Realty Trust VNO to increase its stake in the retailer, easing a restriction put in place last year that had prevented the real-estate investment trust from buying additional J.C. Penney shares. The move, disclosed in a regulatory filing by J.C. Penney on Monday, is the latest development in major shareholder Vornado's involvement with the retailer, which was first disclosed in October. PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES JC Penney Co.'s JCP fiscal second-quarter earnings were flat from the year-ago period as the department-store operator posted lower sales on the exit of its catalog business and smaller margins in a softer-than-expected selling environment early in the quarter and increased promotions. For the third quarter, the company expects earnings of 15 cents to 20 cents a share, including 5 cents in restructuring charges, on comparable store sales growth of 2% to 3% and total sales growth coming in slightly below that view due to the catalog exit.

Headlines.Author: Melodie Warner
Headlines.Headline: Dream On Me Recalls 22,000 Drop-side Cribs

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Dream On Me Inc. of Piscataway, N.J., has voluntarily recalled about 22,000 drop-side cribs that could potentially entrap and strangle children, the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission said. The drop-side rail hardware could break or fail, allowing it to detach from the crib. Once it is partially detached, the drop-side rail creates a space between the crib mattress in which a child could become entrapped, strangled or suffocated. A child could also fall out of the crib.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Dream On Me Recalls 22,000 Drop-side Cribs

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: Toys 'R' Us Dec Same-Store Sales Rise For 5th Straight Year In US

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Toys "R" Us Inc.'s same-store sales rose 2.2% in the U.S. in December--the fifth straight year it has reported growth in that region during the most important month for retailers--while total sales also grew. U.S. sales of the toy retailer climbed 5.4% overall in December, helped by the company's pop-up locations and same-store-sales growth. For the nine-week holiday season, U.S. sales grew 5.3%, with online sales noted as a particular strong category. Toys "R" Us said international sales dropped 3.6% in December, reflecting a 5% drop in same-store sales, partially offset by sales contributions from new stores.

Headlines.Author: Liz Moyer
Headlines.Headline: Private Equity Rebound Offers Wall Street Billions In Revenue

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Updates with comment from Credit Suisse banker) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Private equity firms could be a big source of revenue for Wall Street this year as they look to cash out on investments made before the financial crisis. At stake are billions in potential fees for arranging mergers, loans and stock and bond deals for financial sponsors. Last year, big buyout firms collectively paid Wall Street banks $9.9 billion in fees, according to Dealogic. That was more than double the $4.4 billion in fees they paid to banks in 2009 and 14% of Wall Street's total investment banking revenues of $69 billion.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Private Equity Rebound Offers Wall Street Billions In Revenue

Headlines.Author: Kelly Nolan
Headlines.Headline: CREDIT MARKETS: Quiet Tone Ahead Of Key Jobs Report, US Holiday

PARAGRAPH.#text: Thursday marked another relatively quiet day in the credit markets, as action thinned ahead of the upcoming U.S. Labor Day holiday. However, a heftier slate of issuance in investment-grade corporate bonds is expected after the holiday, provided investors have the appetite. There was some encouraging economic news Thursday, which caused Treasury prices to drop. Weekly jobless claims fell more than expected, and July pending home sales unexpectedly grew 5.2%. Friday will bring a key monthly jobs report for August, which will provide yet another barometer for market participants to gauge the strength of the U.S.

The retailer on Friday announced plans to go public again, when it registered to raise as much as $800 million in the IPO. Headlines.Author: Anusha Shrivastava
Headlines.Headline: Lack Of Alternatives Stokes High-Grade Corp Bond Demand

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds issuance details in the 13th paragraph.) NEW YORK -(Dow Jones)- Investors are continuing to flock to investment-grade corporate bonds in an environment with few alternatives for diversification. Issuance is steady, with supply in March already at $65.5 billion, according to Bank of America/Merrill Lynch analysts. There will be "a steady wave of issuance" this week and more after the month and quarter end, said Bill Larkin, portfolio manager at Cabot Money Management in Salem, Mass. "We are seeing more money going into equity but also seeing a strong inflow into bonds because there are no viable alternatives.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: HEARD ON THE STREET: Kid Gloves Off
Headlines.Headline: Kid Gloves Off

PARAGRAPH.#text: ABC has taken out newspaper ads. Cablevision has gone one better. In its fee dispute with the network, Cablevision this week went straight to its subscribers. It programmed set-top boxes to switch to a channel with a recorded message about the dispute whenever they are turned on. The message suggests ABC owner Disney is making "unreasonable" demands partly because of executive bonuses and weak theme parks. Battling Cablevision isn't for the fainthearted.Even the biggest names in commercial real estate are willing to walk away from troubled properties. The latest example is Vornado Realty Trust, which said in a filing it won't fund shortfalls in $217.8 million of nonrecourse debt it owes on a showroom complex in High Point, N.C. It has asked that the loan be transferred to a special servicer. The question: Will Vornado follow through, or is this a negotiating ploy?

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Kid Gloves Off

PARAGRAPH.#text: By A.D. Pruitt Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--As real-estate investment trusts desperately try to hoard cash, shareholders are poised to lose out on some $4.76 billion worth of dividend payments over the next year. This is giving some investors pause given that dividends are the core driver for investing in REITs, which must pay at least 90% of their taxable income out as quarterly payouts. Within the last 10 months, roughly 30% of all listed REITs have suspended, cut or switched to paying part of their dividend in company stock, according to data compiled by BMO Capital Markets.

Headlines.Headline: SmartMoney(12/1) Street Smart: Make Money Like Buffett

PARAGRAPH.#text: Preferred shares are a hybrid security: Like a share of common stock, they represent ownership in a company. But they trade like a bond, often with much lower price swings, both up and down, than common shares. And clearly, they often pay higher dividends. But look closely: Prices can still fall, and companies can cut their dividends. Worse, when a company goes under, preferred-shareholders must line up behind bondholders. Indeed, investors in Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac preferred stock got wiped out when the government took over the firms.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: SmartMoney(12/1) Street Smart: Make Money Like Buffett

#text: (This article was originally published Friday) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Moody's Investors Service cut its credit rating on beleaguered General Growth Properties Inc.

because of uncertainty about its liquidity. Moody's also warned of possible future downgrades as it lowered its senior secured bank debt and senior unsecured debt ratings one notch further into junk territory to Ba3. in size. But analysts warn that the opportunity for cheap acquisitions and
big returns has passed.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Vornado Is Buying,
But Analysts Warn
Timing May Be Bad
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
David D.
Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline: Simon DeBartolo to Buy REIT

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Simon DeBartolo Group
 agreed to pay
$4.8 billion for Corporate Property Investors, which owns two dozen malls
and New York's General Motors Building. The purchase firmly establishes
Simon DeBartolo as the largest U.S. owner of retail properties and signals
that the commercial real-estate market is heating up again.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Simon DeBartolo to Buy REIT
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
Kathryn M.
Welling
Headlines.Headline: Mighty Mike - Cover Story

PARAGRAPH.#text:
In an interview, respected investor Michael Price discusses his
favorites, including Chase Manhattan, Sunbeam, Florida East Coast and St.
Joe. What GM's stock buyback means. A word about Dow Jones.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Mighty Mike - Cover Story

Headlines.Author:
Barry
Vinocur
Headlines.Headline: Siamese Surgery

PARAGRAPH.#text: The Treasury's paired-share REIT's proposal.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Siamese Surgery

Headlines.Author: Gregory Zuckerman
Headlines.Headline:
Casino-Takeover Contracts
Rumored to Pick-Up Pace

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Investors are betting
 that the pace
of consolidation in the gambling industry will pick up. Speculation that
more deals are in the pipeline has helped the Dow Jones index of casino
stocks rise 11.31% so far this year.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Casino-Takeover Contracts
Rumored to Pick-Up Pace
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
David D.
Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline: REITs Could Hit the Jackpot

PARAGRAPH.#text:
REITs are
becoming
 the talk of Las Vegas since Crescent
agreed to buy Station Casinos. The deal will create a casino company that
will nearly avoid corporate income taxes, a prospect that could change both
the gambling business and REITs.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: REITs Could Hit the Jackpot
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Mitchell Pacelle
Headlines.Headline:
The Kennedy Clan
Decides to Cash In
Its Last Big Business

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The Kennedy family agreed
 to sell
Chicago's Merchandise Mart, along with other properties, to Vornado Realty
Trust for $575 million and the assumption of debt. The proposed sale is
expected to be announced Monday.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
The Kennedy Clan
Decides to Cash In
Its Last Big Business
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
Vito J.
Racanelli
Headlines.Headline:
Rio Hotel Offers More Than Just Takeover
Mania

PARAGRAPH.#text:
January 22, 1998
As takeover fever pushes casino stocks higher, Rio Hotel & Casino looks
like a solid bet on several counts.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Rio Hotel Offers More Than Just Takeover
Mania

Headlines.Author:
David D.
Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline: Vornado, Kennedy Family in Talks

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Vornado Realty Trust
 is in talks to
buy Chicago's Merchandise Mart and other properties from the Kennedy
family, say people close to the talks.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Vornado, Kennedy Family in Talks
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Christina Binkley
Headlines.Headline: Circus Circus CEO to Resign

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Circus Circus Enterprises
 said Clyde
T. Turner will resign as chairman, chief executive and a director. Mr.
Turner had rejuvenated the casino company with its 1995 acquisition of Gold
Strike Resorts, only to watch it sink into the doldrums last year.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Circus Circus CEO to Resign
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Neal Templin
Headlines.Headline: Crescent to Buy Station Casinos

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Crescent agreed
 to pay $635 million
in stock for Station Casinos. The move could encourage other real-estate
investment trusts to decide to enter the gambling business.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Crescent to Buy Station Casinos
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Stephane Fitch
Headlines.Headline: Arden Realty to Acquire LBA

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Arden Realty
 agreed to acquire LBA
Properties for about $600 million, according to people familiar with the
situation. The deal would increase Arden's property portfolio by 5 million
square feet, or 57%.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Arden Realty to Acquire LBA
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
David D.
Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline: REITs Diversify to Sustain Growth

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Even
as
 the real estate boom continues, it's getting
harder to make money in real estate. With oversupply a looming threat, some
big REITs are responding to rising prices by spinning off new firms,
branching out into new fields, or seeking acquisitions abroad.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: REITs Diversify to Sustain Growth
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
Peter
Slatin
Headlines.Headline: Prodigal Funds

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Pension funds accelerate REIT investment, raising questions about market
impact.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Prodigal Funds

Headlines.Author: Mitchell Pacelle
Headlines.Headline: Mansion Sells for $36 Million

PARAGRAPH.#text:
A New York mansion
 was sold last week
to German investors for $36 million. The $1,300-a-square-foot deal for the
building that houses Polo Ralph Lauren's flagship store is the priciest
real-estate deal since the 1980s.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Mansion Sells for $36 Million
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Neal Templin
Headlines.Headline:
Crescent Spins Off a Big Success
In Its Tax-Paying Operating Firm

PARAGRAPH.#text:
A

REITs advantage
 is its tax-free status. But
Crescent Real Estate has caused a stir by creating a separate tax-paying
company, Crescent Operating, that is handling deals traditionally
off-limits to REITs.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Crescent Spins Off a Big Success
In Its Tax-Paying Operating Firm
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
Peter
Slatin
Headlines.Headline: Cash Is Preferred

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The sale of Leona Helmsley's vast holdings will likely be a watershed in
real estate.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Cash Is Preferred

Headlines.Headline: Planet Hollywood to Build Casino

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Planet Hollywood said
 it will build a
1,000-room hotel and a casino in Las Vegas with Aladdin Gaming. The $250
million hotel is expected to be completed in late 1999. Separately, Planet
Hollywood said profit jumped 30% in the third quarter, while revenue
increased 34%.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Planet Hollywood to Build Casino
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
David D.
Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline: Leading REITs Lose Ground

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The
leading
 real-estate investment trust indexes closed
down slightly Tuesday as investors moved to take part in the market's
strong recovery.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Leading REITs Lose Ground
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Peter
Slatin

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Why many private property companies refuse to go public despite the
temptations.

Gold

Headlines.Author:
David D.
Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline: REITs Buy Into Cold-Storage

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Vornado and Crescent
 agreed to buy
two cold-storage firms for $289 million, plus assumption of $660 million of
debt, as real-estate firms continue to move into new areas.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: REITs Buy Into Cold-Storage
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Richard Gibson
Headlines.Headline: Planet Hollywood Enters Deal

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Planet Hollywood
 will take a 20%
stake in a venture that will renovate the Hotel Pennsylvania near New
York's Madison Square Garden into the Official All Star Hotel. The new
hotel will feature a sports motif.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Planet Hollywood Enters Deal
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
David D.
Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline:
Five-and-Dime Chain's End
Sparks a Real-Estate Rush

PARAGRAPH.#text:
W
hen
Woolworth
 last month announced plans to close its
last 400 domestic general-merchandise stores, the retailer created a
real-estate bonanza. Some of the grungy variety stores sit on valuable
locations, from New Orleans's Bourbon Street to New York's 42nd Street.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Five-and-Dime Chain's End
Sparks a Real-Estate Rush
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author:
David D.
Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline: Paper Clips for Vornado Realty

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Steven
Roth
, chairman and chief executive of Vornado
Realty Trust, says the company plans to create an independent taxable
public corporation that will have an agreement to share business
opportunities with the REIT -- an arrangement that analysts call
"paper-clipped stocks."

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Paper Clips for Vornado Realty
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: David D. Kirkpatrick
Headlines.Headline: Big Names Mean Big Price

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Investors
in
 Vornado Realty Trust are making a high-stakes
bet that two savvy executives can run a real-estate investment trust like a
buy-out fund.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Big Names Mean Big Price
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ann Carrns
Headlines.Headline: Vornado Realty to Buy Mendik

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Vornado Realty Trust
 agreed to
acquire Mendik, an owner and manager of commercial office properties in New
York, in a deal valued at $654 million.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Vornado Realty to Buy Mendik
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Vornado Realty to Buy Mendik

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Vornado Realty
 Trust signed a letter
of intent to buy Mendik, two analysts familiar with the deal said,
potentially blocking Mendik's planned initial public offering.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Vornado Realty to Buy Mendik
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition
